The paper discusses the use of Reference Publication Years Spectroscopy (RPYS) to identify long-term impact and historically constitutive citations in the field of Information and Library Science. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to sub-categories related to information retrieval (cs.IR), human-computer interaction (cs.HC), computational linguistics (cs.CL), and cryptography (cs.CR). However, given the focus on clustering documents based on shared intellectual histories, the paper is most likely to belong to the sub-category of digital libraries (cs.DL).
